01:36.304 --> 01:40.642
{\an5}STEVE:
<i>Well, I know what all you guys</i>
<i>are thinking.</i>

01:40.725 --> 01:43.812
<i>Yeah, you're thinking that</i>
<i>Steve-o is a little crazy,</i>

01:43.895 --> 01:45.355
<i>a little cuckoo,</i>
<i>a little whacko.</i>

01:45.438 --> 01:47.690
<i>Well, it wasn't until I nailed</i>

01:47.774 --> 01:48.483
<i>that half-court shot</i>
<i>at the Laker game...</i>

01:48.566 --> 01:51.069
BRANDON:
<i>Here he goes again.</i>

01:51.152 --> 01:54.072
{\an5}STEVE:
<i>That I realized that it was a</i>
<i>once in a lifetime phenomenon.</i>

01:54.155 --> 01:56.324
Like us graduating from high
school will never happen again.

01:56.407 --> 01:59.160
Listen, Steve, I may
not get to graduate

01:59.244 --> 02:00.411
{\an1}if I don't go back to
the library soon, okay?

02:00.495 --> 02:02.372
{\an1}I've got two more
final exams

02:02.455 --> 02:04.249
I have to take
Yeah, yeah,

02:04.332 --> 02:06.501
and I've still gotta get
Mrs. Teasley to sign off

02:06.584 --> 02:08.711
{\an1}before I can graduate,
but that doesn't stop me

02:08.794 --> 02:12.048
{\an1}from wanting to do something
special, with you guys.

02:12.131 --> 02:13.341
Look, Steve, what you're
proposing here

02:13.424 --> 02:16.052
is an inspired idea,
I'll give you that.

02:16.135 --> 02:18.388
But I just don't think we
have the time to pull it off.

02:18.471 --> 02:20.390
{\an1}Brandon, don't worry,
I'll get the van,

02:20.473 --> 02:23.143
{\an1}I've already got
the paint and the canvas,

02:23.226 --> 02:25.228
{\an4}so all I need to do
is to consult with
Donna about the design.

02:25.311 --> 02:29.232
Well, I'd like to help, but
couldn't we get in trouble?

02:29.315 --> 02:31.067
{\an3}What, like getting
arrested for trespassing

02:31.150 --> 02:32.610
{\an3}and defacing private property,
that kind of trouble?

02:32.694 --> 02:35.196
{\an1}Andrea, don't you want people
to know that we were here?

02:35.280 --> 02:37.240
{\an1}Don't you want people
to know that we mattered?

02:37.323 --> 02:39.242
I say we do it.

02:39.325 --> 02:40.368
I'm in.

02:40.451 --> 02:43.788
{\an1}Well, then,
do we have a pact?

02:43.872 --> 02:46.875
Do we go for the gold?

02:49.460 --> 02:51.754
Ah, I didn't want to get any
sleep on grad night anyway.

02:53.131 --> 02:54.215
ALL:
Yeah!

02:54.299 --> 02:56.509
("Pomp and Circumstance"
playing)

03:22.327 --> 03:23.328
(laughter, indistinct
conversations)

03:28.333 --> 03:31.502
♪ ♪

03:35.882 --> 03:37.383
(music swells)

03:40.386 --> 03:43.640
{\an1}I can't believe I have
known some of these people

03:43.723 --> 03:44.599
for, like, 12 years.

03:44.682 --> 03:47.852
{\an3}It's definitely time
to meet some new ones.

03:47.936 --> 03:50.313
{\an1}Come on, are you a little bit
nostalgic about graduating?

03:50.396 --> 03:51.606
Yes, I am, but I just

03:51.689 --> 03:53.274
{\an3}want to get this stupid
rehearsal over with.

03:53.358 --> 03:54.734
I mean, what's the big deal?

03:54.817 --> 03:57.153
They call your name, you go up,
you get your diploma,

03:57.236 --> 03:58.154
you sit down, you go home.

03:58.237 --> 04:00.490
{\an1}Well, for someone who
almost had to stay home

04:00.573 --> 04:02.575
and miss the whole thing, they
can rehearse me all they want.

04:16.130 --> 04:18.298
Down, set... hike.

04:21.803 --> 04:23.179
Yeah!

04:23.262 --> 04:25.223
(laughing)

04:27.266 --> 04:28.851
Did you see
that, Bren?

04:28.935 --> 04:30.186
Did you see that?

04:30.269 --> 04:31.688
You're supposed to
be the secondary.

04:31.771 --> 04:33.189
Come on, stick 'em!

04:33.272 --> 04:34.357
Dylan, the teams aren't
exactly balanced, man.

04:34.440 --> 04:35.441
Well, they're about to be
a little more unbalanced,

04:35.525 --> 04:38.361
{\an1}'cause I'm outta here, babe.
Cover for me, all right?

04:38.444 --> 04:40.363
{\an3}I'm meeting a
Hey, where guy for lunch.

04:40.446 --> 04:40.905
Hey listen, you guys
cover for me, too.

04:40.989 --> 04:42.657
I gotta go to the Blaze

04:42.740 --> 04:44.158
and see if the senior wills
have been turned in.

04:44.242 --> 04:45.159
Later. Later.

04:45.243 --> 04:47.370
(feedback)

04:47.453 --> 04:48.496
{\an5}ANDREA:
Testing, testing,
one two, three.

04:48.579 --> 04:51.249
Testing, testing, testing.

04:51.332 --> 04:53.376
Okay, okay, that's fine.

04:53.459 --> 04:55.712
{\an3}You want to practice
your speech?

04:55.795 --> 04:57.171
No, thanks.

04:57.255 --> 04:58.548
I'd rather not over-rehearse.

04:58.631 --> 05:02.385
{\an1}Well, uh, public oratory
tends to be most compelling

05:02.468 --> 05:07.056
{\an1}when the confluence
of language is unfettered

05:07.140 --> 05:10.393
{\an1}with the constraints
of excessive repetition,

05:10.476 --> 05:11.894
if you know what I mean.

05:11.978 --> 05:14.397
Yeah, that's fine, Andrea.

05:14.480 --> 05:15.064
That's fine.

05:18.276 --> 05:20.737
Hey, hey, young David,

05:20.820 --> 05:21.446
{\an3}feeling a little
burned out, brother?

05:21.529 --> 05:22.572
Who me?

05:22.655 --> 05:24.574
{\an1}I love taking six finals
in three days.

05:24.657 --> 05:28.578
What's my name again?

05:28.661 --> 05:30.580
Just be glad it's
not Steve Sanders.

05:33.291 --> 05:37.211
Read any good books
lately, bro?

05:37.295 --> 05:38.880
That's not very
funny, Brandon.

05:38.963 --> 05:39.589
Come on, Steve, look
on the bright side.

05:39.672 --> 05:42.592
It's the last day of school.

05:42.675 --> 05:45.219
{\an1}Mrs. Teasley cannot make
you go to detention,

05:45.303 --> 05:46.429
after you graduate.

05:46.512 --> 05:47.221
If I graduate.

05:47.305 --> 05:48.306
{\an1}Steve...

05:48.389 --> 05:50.266
{\an3}No, why else would
she release everyone

05:50.349 --> 05:51.476
from detention but me, huh?

05:51.559 --> 05:54.103
Maybe 'cause you're the only
one who broke into the school

05:54.187 --> 05:56.481
to try to change your grades
with that stupid legacy key.

05:56.564 --> 05:58.316
You didn't see the way
this lady looked at me

05:58.399 --> 06:00.318
when she told me to report
to her office after school.

06:00.401 --> 06:00.943
Why are you so paranoid?

06:01.027 --> 06:01.778
{\an3}I'm telling you,
Brandon,

06:01.861 --> 06:04.447
{\an3}I can read this
lady like a book.

06:04.530 --> 06:06.240
{\an3}She's got a hidden agenda
here and I know it.

06:06.324 --> 06:09.410
Otherwise, I'd be at the
graduation rehearsal right now.

06:09.494 --> 06:11.120
JIM:
<i>What do we got here?</i>

06:11.204 --> 06:12.288
<i>Bacon cheeseburger for you,</i>

06:12.371 --> 06:15.625
{\an3}and cottage cheese and
fruit cup for me.

06:15.708 --> 06:17.752
Is that what I have
to look forward to?

06:17.835 --> 06:20.338
{\an3}Only if you eat
too many of those.

06:20.421 --> 06:21.255
So, how do you
liked Berkeley?

06:21.339 --> 06:23.299
{\an1}Well, I could definitely
see myself living

06:23.382 --> 06:24.509
{\an1}in a little place
overlooking the bay,

06:24.592 --> 06:26.135
assuming that I can get in.

06:26.219 --> 06:28.638
{\an3}Well, there's always
California University.

06:28.721 --> 06:30.556
{\an3}Brandon's very excited
about going there.

06:30.640 --> 06:33.309
I won't be goin' anywhere until
I get those test scores back.

06:33.392 --> 06:34.602
{\an3}You know, I think it was
a very wise decision

06:34.685 --> 06:36.813
to take those
SAT's again.

06:36.896 --> 06:37.980
{\an1}Well, it was like
my dad said,

06:38.064 --> 06:41.150
{\an1}the only way to prove to those
bastards that I didn't cheat

06:41.234 --> 06:43.986
{\an1}was to take the test again
and raise my scores.

06:44.070 --> 06:45.822
{\an1}Did I tell you I've
been writing about him?

06:45.905 --> 06:48.991
No. Your mom did.

06:49.075 --> 06:50.993
How is Iris?

06:51.077 --> 06:53.746
Oh, she's... Iris.

06:55.414 --> 06:56.541
She is concerned about

06:56.624 --> 06:57.708
{\an3}what you're going to do
with all your money.

06:57.792 --> 07:01.671
What does she think?

07:01.754 --> 07:03.631
I mean, does she really think
that I'm gonna blow it all?

07:03.714 --> 07:06.634
{\an1}Does she really think I can't
handle my own affairs yet?

07:06.717 --> 07:08.386
No, that's not it.

07:08.469 --> 07:10.346
So, why doesn't she just say
a mantra, or whatever she does,

07:10.429 --> 07:10.680
and have her accountant
cut the check already?

07:10.763 --> 07:12.640
She did.

07:12.723 --> 07:15.893
Really?

07:17.603 --> 07:20.106
That's it right there?

07:23.276 --> 07:24.193
Better wipe your hands.

07:24.277 --> 07:26.279
{\an3}You don't want to get
grease on a check

07:26.362 --> 07:27.697
{\an3}with this
many zeroes in it.

07:30.825 --> 07:33.369
That's a lot of money.

07:33.452 --> 07:36.706
Yes, it is.

07:36.789 --> 07:38.332
{\an1}(sighs)

07:38.416 --> 07:41.377
(bell ringing)

07:41.460 --> 07:43.880
Hello, West Beverly.

07:43.963 --> 07:45.923
This is Eric Ruben.

07:46.007 --> 07:48.551
I've got only one
thing to say...

07:48.634 --> 07:50.678
school's out for summer!

07:50.761 --> 07:54.682
♪ School's out for summer... ♪

07:54.765 --> 07:58.186
Hey, how'd it go?

07:58.269 --> 07:59.937
I blew it. I flunked.

08:00.021 --> 08:01.230
It's over.

08:01.314 --> 08:03.107
{\an1}He says this
after every test.

08:03.191 --> 08:04.358
It's like a little ritual.

08:04.442 --> 08:05.776
There were a hundred
multiple choice questions.

08:05.860 --> 08:07.945
With two minutes to go,

08:08.029 --> 08:09.363
I realized I had been
misnumbering

08:09.447 --> 08:10.239
since around the mid-50's.

08:10.323 --> 08:13.409
{\an3}Well, chemistry's
hard for everybody..

08:13.492 --> 08:14.827
Yeah, right.

08:17.663 --> 08:19.457
{\an3}Who's that?

08:21.459 --> 08:24.253
The new voice of West Beverly.

08:24.337 --> 08:26.797
♪ No more books ♪

08:26.881 --> 08:30.426
♪ No more teacher's
dirty looks ♪

08:30.509 --> 08:32.260
{\an6}TEASLEY:
I've warned you
time and time again

08:32.345 --> 08:33.804
until I was blue in the face.

08:33.888 --> 08:34.722
{\an3}And that's why
I called your parents!

08:34.804 --> 08:37.265
So, don't even think
about coming in here

08:37.350 --> 08:40.186
{\an3}looking like that
next year!

08:41.895 --> 08:47.109
{\an1}You are so lucky to be
getting out of this place.

08:49.654 --> 08:49.862
(knocking)

08:49.946 --> 08:51.948
Come in.

08:52.031 --> 08:55.409
Mrs. Teasley, am I catching
you at a bad time?

08:55.493 --> 08:57.703
No, not at all. Come on in.

09:00.665 --> 09:03.251
Mrs. Teasley, before we start,

09:03.334 --> 09:05.378
can I saNo.omething?

09:05.461 --> 09:07.463
{\an3}You know, Steven,
it's been my experience

09:07.546 --> 09:11.592
that every class has at least
one unredeemable student--

09:11.676 --> 09:14.303
a student whose values
are so warped

09:14.387 --> 09:17.598
{\an3}that punishment has
no effect.

09:17.682 --> 09:19.475
Is this your way of telling me

09:19.558 --> 09:20.059
that I'm not graduating
tomorrow?

09:20.142 --> 09:22.770
May I finish, please?

09:22.853 --> 09:26.357
Sure. Knock yourself out.

09:26.440 --> 09:30.653
And I realized early on

09:30.736 --> 09:32.863
that you were the member
of the Class of '93

09:32.947 --> 09:37.660
{\an3}whom I would have
to write off...

09:37.743 --> 09:38.911
{\an3}until I realized
I'd misjudged you.

09:41.414 --> 09:42.832
You had?

09:42.915 --> 09:44.834
Your grades since December
have improved.

09:44.917 --> 09:48.296
No doubt due to the extra
study time in detention.

09:48.379 --> 09:51.299
{\an6}But the real
awakening came
when I found out

09:51.382 --> 09:52.341
that on the day after

09:52.425 --> 09:54.343
you had won $10,000 for
making a half-court shot

09:54.427 --> 09:55.469
at the Laker game,

09:55.553 --> 09:57.138
someone donated $10,000

09:57.221 --> 10:00.141
to the Alvarado Street
Summer Camp Fund.

10:00.224 --> 10:01.892
Really?

10:01.976 --> 10:04.145
Someone whose return address

10:04.228 --> 10:05.229
happened to be
<i>The Hartley House.</i>

10:05.313 --> 10:08.816
What a coincidence.

10:08.899 --> 10:10.234
What a wonderful thing to do.

10:10.318 --> 10:12.361
STEVE:
<i>Bro! Bro!</i>

10:12.445 --> 10:13.738
Mrs. Teasley's actually
gonna write me a letter

10:13.821 --> 10:15.865
of recommendation to any
college I want to go to.

10:15.948 --> 10:17.199
Do you know what this means?

10:17.283 --> 10:18.909
{\an1}This means that I get to go
to any college I want to.

10:18.993 --> 10:21.704
I'm gonna go to California
University with you, man.

10:21.787 --> 10:22.830
{\an1}Steve, Steve, if you kiss
me, I'm gonna slap you.

10:22.913 --> 10:24.874
{\an3}And you didn't think
she liked me, did you?

10:24.957 --> 10:27.543
She loves me, love.

10:27.626 --> 10:29.170
She loves me,
'cause I'm...

10:31.797 --> 10:32.798
For a year I wanted
to do that to you!

10:32.882 --> 10:35.217
Yes!

10:35.301 --> 10:37.720
Oh, hey, the senior wills are
finally here. How do they look?

10:37.803 --> 10:39.055
I haven't had time
to check them out.

10:39.138 --> 10:40.389
I'm sure they're fine.

10:40.473 --> 10:40.931
Still working on
your speech, huh?

10:41.015 --> 10:43.059
I'm just fine-tuning it.

10:43.142 --> 10:45.227
{\an1}Mm-hmm, Andrea, you've been
fine-tuning it for a week now.

10:45.311 --> 10:47.104
{\an1}I'm sure it's as fine-tuned
as it's gonna get.

10:47.188 --> 10:48.272
It's still awful.

10:48.356 --> 10:49.065
Andrea, come on.

10:49.148 --> 10:50.483
No, I mean it.

10:50.566 --> 10:52.068
It's pretentious, trivial,
wishy-washy.

10:52.151 --> 10:54.612
I don't even know what I can
do with it anymore, Brandon.

10:54.695 --> 10:57.406
{\an1}Would it help you
to run it by me later?

10:57.490 --> 10:58.908
Brandon, you're great.

10:58.991 --> 11:00.701
I love you.

11:00.785 --> 11:03.746
The best.

11:03.829 --> 11:06.123
("Louie Louie" playing)

11:06.207 --> 11:07.750
Donna, wake up your boyfriend

11:07.833 --> 11:10.211
{\an1}and tell him to put on
No! Shh!ing shoes!

11:10.294 --> 11:11.253
{\an1}With all the studying
and rehearsing

11:11.337 --> 11:13.255
for the Senior Breakfast,
he's completely drained.

11:13.339 --> 11:16.092
He's missing the Last Day of
the Peach Pit Party right here!

11:16.175 --> 11:17.927
{\an4}NAT:
Last day at
the Peach Pit?

11:18.010 --> 11:20.221
Last day of high school.

11:20.304 --> 11:22.598
{\an3}It's the last day
of high school.

11:22.681 --> 11:24.850
{\an3}Nat, don't worry, because
we're not gonna abandon you

11:24.934 --> 11:26.310
{\an3}just because
we're graduating!

11:26.394 --> 11:29.146
(whooping, shouting)

11:29.230 --> 11:31.816
GrBig boy! Big boy!s!

11:31.899 --> 11:33.609
Where's Andrea?

11:33.692 --> 11:36.278
{\an1}Ah, she had some last-minute
worries to take care of.

11:36.362 --> 11:37.947
So, how are
the Senior Wills looking?

11:38.030 --> 11:38.948
Outstanding.

11:39.031 --> 11:40.658
Did you bring us
our advance copy?

11:40.741 --> 11:42.076
{\an1}Negative, young Kelly,
you're gonna have to wait

11:42.159 --> 11:43.661
{\an1}to get yours
at the Senior Breakfast

11:43.744 --> 11:45.079
just like everyone else.

11:45.162 --> 11:47.456
How come I don't get to leave
anything in the Senior Will?

11:47.540 --> 11:49.834
Yeah, and Nat ought to be an
honorary member of the class.

11:49.917 --> 11:52.461
Okay, Mr. Bussichio, what
would you like to leave?

11:52.545 --> 11:55.297
{\an3}Well, I know what I'd like
to leave your father.

11:55.381 --> 11:56.799
{\an3}(laughs):
That karaoke machine

11:56.882 --> 11:57.925
{\an3}that almost put me
out of business.

11:58.008 --> 11:59.760
{\an3}So, Nat, what would
you leave me?

11:59.844 --> 12:03.139
Uh... that singing group that
came in here to serenade you.

12:03.222 --> 12:03.806
Color Me Badd.

12:03.889 --> 12:04.807
What about me, Nat?

12:04.890 --> 12:07.768
Oh, that one's easy...

12:07.852 --> 12:08.936
Laverne.

12:10.104 --> 12:11.772
Wait, who's Laverne?

12:11.856 --> 12:14.817
{\an4}STEVE:
She's that crazy chick
who used to work for Nat.

12:14.900 --> 12:16.986
(East Coast accent):
Sir! Welcome!

12:17.069 --> 12:20.406
{\an3}I'm Laverne.
Charmed, I'm sure.

12:20.489 --> 12:21.282
{\an3}NAT:
I don't get it.

12:21.365 --> 12:23.826
Hey, don't you
What worry, pops.ween?

12:23.909 --> 12:25.828
{\an3}You'll get no trick-or-treats
with <i> this</i> little lady.

12:25.911 --> 12:28.414
I'm strictly a class act.

12:28.497 --> 12:32.793
A 100% U.S.-certified
hostess with the mostess.

12:32.877 --> 12:34.545
{\an3}The special plate for
today is spaghetti.

12:34.628 --> 12:37.465
It has meatballs on it,
with a red sauce--

12:37.548 --> 12:39.175
um, I think it's tomato.

12:39.258 --> 12:41.385
{\an3}And the soup is vegetable
with beefy beef.

12:41.469 --> 12:43.053
Very tasty with saltines.

12:43.137 --> 12:44.638
{\an3}And for dessert,
we have pie.

12:44.722 --> 12:47.391
We have peach pie, cherry pie,
apple pie, pecan pie,

12:47.475 --> 12:49.685
lemon pie, cream pie
and honey pie.

12:49.768 --> 12:50.394
{\an3}But if you want
pizza pie,

12:50.478 --> 12:52.146
you gotta go across the street.

12:52.229 --> 12:53.689
Ask for Guido--
he'll take care of ya.

12:53.772 --> 12:54.690
So what will it be?

12:54.774 --> 12:57.109
{\an1}Maybe we could get Laverne
to make an appearance

12:57.193 --> 13:00.738
Oh, I don't know,
aif you're nice to her..

13:00.821 --> 13:02.364
{\an1}BRANDON:
Hey, Jordan!

13:02.448 --> 13:04.033
Mr. Grad-u-ate.

13:04.116 --> 13:05.367
Congratulations.

13:05.451 --> 13:05.993
Andrea told me your
valedictorian speech

13:06.076 --> 13:08.787
was vThanks.quent.

13:08.871 --> 13:10.748
{\an3}But I think
she's exaggerating.

13:10.831 --> 13:12.082
Is she around?

13:12.166 --> 13:14.418
No, she said she had some stuff
she has to take care of.

13:14.502 --> 13:17.046
{\an3}I guess she forgot
I was coming.

13:17.129 --> 13:20.174
Well, tell her I stopped by
and wishI will.od luck.

13:20.257 --> 13:21.717
Hey, Jordan,

13:21.800 --> 13:23.886
um... do me a favor.

13:23.969 --> 13:26.096
{\an1}When you guys go back
to New Haven,

13:26.180 --> 13:28.349
{\an1}don't let Andrea
drive herself too crazy.

13:28.432 --> 13:31.560
{\an3}I won't, if she
ends up going there.

13:31.644 --> 13:33.145
What are you talking about?
She's been dreaming

13:33.229 --> 13:34.855
about going to Yale
since she was born.

13:34.939 --> 13:36.190
She didn't tell you?

13:36.273 --> 13:38.567
She's having a lot of
second thoughts about going.

13:39.652 --> 13:40.903
Well, maybe she did
mention something.

13:40.986 --> 13:44.365
Did it ever occur to you

13:44.448 --> 13:46.909
why she's having
second thoughts?

13:58.671 --> 14:00.714
(crickets chirping)

14:01.215 --> 14:05.219
(Brenda laughs)

14:05.302 --> 14:06.929
(laughs):
Hi, guys.

14:07.012 --> 14:08.055
What's wrong?

14:08.138 --> 14:11.433
{\an1}You got an envelope
from the admissions office

14:11.517 --> 14:12.935
{\an1}of the University
of Minnesota.

14:13.018 --> 14:15.104
Thick or thin?

14:15.187 --> 14:17.773
{\an3}Very thick.

14:17.856 --> 14:20.192
{\an3}Looks like we've
been admitted.

14:25.864 --> 14:27.825
Ew.

14:27.908 --> 14:29.743
What do you want me
to do with these?

14:29.827 --> 14:32.329
{\an1}Oh, God, relics
from the bimbo era.

14:32.413 --> 14:33.956
I'll take those
if you don't want them.

14:34.039 --> 14:35.124
You don't know
how much room you're going

14:35.207 --> 14:36.208
to have in the new place...
wherever that is.

14:36.292 --> 14:39.795
I was assuming you both
would be living in a dorm.

14:39.878 --> 14:41.463
Perish the thought.

14:41.547 --> 14:43.132
{\an3}I haven't even been
accepted anywhere yet.

14:43.215 --> 14:46.510
Well, I guess I'll put these
in the "maybe" pile.

14:47.219 --> 14:49.763
{\an1}God, talk
about change.

14:49.847 --> 14:52.182
New house, new school,
a new life.

14:52.266 --> 14:54.476
Hi, froggy.

14:54.560 --> 14:55.978
I know, it's like you work
so hard to get to the end

14:56.061 --> 14:58.188
of something, and all of a
sudden it starts all over again.

14:58.272 --> 15:01.650
Yeah, but not from square one.

15:01.734 --> 15:04.653
I mean,
you're actually cool now.

15:04.737 --> 15:06.822
Nothing compared
to what you used to be.

15:06.905 --> 15:09.033
Wait, are you saying
that I was once a geek?

15:09.116 --> 15:11.201
Well, I remember
what you were like

15:11.285 --> 15:14.455
when Mel and Jackie
started dating.

15:14.538 --> 15:15.831
Hey, Kel.

15:15.914 --> 15:17.166
Hi.

15:17.249 --> 15:19.418
I heard your mom and my dad

15:19.501 --> 15:20.961
had a pretty swinging time
last night.

15:21.045 --> 15:24.465
That's not what I heard.

15:24.548 --> 15:26.467
No, seriously.

15:26.550 --> 15:29.011
I think they already set up
another date for this week.

15:29.261 --> 15:31.388
Wouldn't it be cool

15:31.472 --> 15:33.015
if we ended up
step-brother and step-sister?

15:33.098 --> 15:36.185
(eerie music playing)

15:36.268 --> 15:39.146
(shower running)

15:39.229 --> 15:41.231
(water stops)

15:46.820 --> 15:48.864
David, get out of here!

15:48.947 --> 15:49.782
{\an1}Mom!

15:49.865 --> 15:51.742
I'm sorry, I didn't know
you were in here.

15:51.825 --> 15:53.911
Get out of here, now!

15:53.994 --> 15:55.162
I-I'm sorry...

15:57.122 --> 15:58.999
Oh, my God.

15:59.083 --> 16:00.751
(groans)

16:03.921 --> 16:07.675
Okay, I've apologized for that
numerous times already.

16:07.758 --> 16:09.718
I know, I know.

16:09.802 --> 16:12.221
Living with you actually
turned out to be kind of fun.

16:14.264 --> 16:15.557
I just wish Mel and Jackie's

16:15.641 --> 16:16.975
marriage had worked out.

16:17.059 --> 16:19.353
Yeah, well, at least you got
a baby sister out of it.

16:19.436 --> 16:21.397
And a brother.

16:24.817 --> 16:26.735
Anybody want some more fudge?

16:26.819 --> 16:28.737
I think weNo. fine, Mom.

16:28.821 --> 16:30.239
{\an1}Okay, on the plus side
for Minnesota,

16:30.322 --> 16:32.241
{\an1}it has an exceptional
drama department,

16:32.324 --> 16:34.618
{\an1}you can take your
junior year abroad...

16:34.702 --> 16:36.704
{\an3}You can do that through
California University, too.

16:36.787 --> 16:37.913
Not in Paris.

16:37.996 --> 16:39.748
You've already
been to Paris.

16:39.832 --> 16:40.791
Brandon, what is it with you?

16:40.874 --> 16:45.254
{\an3}Look, I understand why
you applied to Minnesota,

16:45.337 --> 16:48.590
{\an3}but seeing as everyone's
getting along so well now,

16:48.674 --> 16:51.427
{\an3}California University is
rated as a much better school.

16:51.510 --> 16:53.762
{\an3}Not to mention the fact--
Dad, you'll appreciate this--

16:53.846 --> 16:55.097
it's also a much
cheaper school.

16:55.180 --> 16:57.725
{\an6}BRENDA:
Brandon, just
because I got in,

16:57.808 --> 16:59.351
doesn't mean
I have to go.

16:59.435 --> 17:00.978
{\an3}Fine, then I guess
it's settled.

17:01.061 --> 17:03.439
{\an1}Well, I don't think we should
be too hasty about this.

17:03.522 --> 17:05.273
I'd like to keep
my options open.

17:05.357 --> 17:07.818
{\an4}JIM:
Well, another plus for
California University,

17:07.901 --> 17:09.278
aside from being a great school.

17:09.361 --> 17:10.654
Thank you.

17:10.738 --> 17:11.113
All your friends are here.

17:11.195 --> 17:13.198
And we're here.

17:15.826 --> 17:18.119
{\an1}I don't have to make
my decision right now, do I?

17:18.203 --> 17:19.454
(Brandon chuckles,
doorbell rings)

17:19.538 --> 17:21.080
I'll get it.

17:21.165 --> 17:22.290
Sorry, Mom.

17:22.374 --> 17:25.669
Listen, Brenda,

17:25.752 --> 17:28.088
this going away to school, um...

17:28.172 --> 17:30.424
it doesn't have anything
to do with Dylan, does it?

17:30.507 --> 17:32.468
Mom, this is the '90s.

17:32.551 --> 17:34.470
What kind of insecure
wuss chooses a college

17:34.553 --> 17:36.346
{\an1}based on where
some guy is going?

17:36.430 --> 17:38.015
Hi!

17:39.016 --> 17:40.309
What are you eating?

17:41.685 --> 17:44.354
"And so, as we travel
the unfathomable paths

17:44.438 --> 17:46.023
{\an1}"which weave before us,
we do so with the clarity

17:46.106 --> 17:47.816
of our vision and the certainty
of our stride..."

17:47.900 --> 17:49.443
Wait, do you think
that that should be

17:49.526 --> 17:51.111
{\an1}the "strength
of our convictions"

17:51.195 --> 17:52.321
{\an1}or the "strength
of our certainty"?

17:52.404 --> 17:55.491
{\an3}I'm still back on
"the unfathomable path."

17:55.574 --> 17:57.159
It's the worst, isn't it?

17:57.242 --> 17:59.286
{\an3}No, no, no,
it's not the worst.

17:59.369 --> 18:03.332
It just seems like you're
trying to conform to some image

18:03.415 --> 18:04.333
of what you think you
should be saying

18:04.416 --> 18:07.336
instead of deciding what
it is you want to say.

18:07.419 --> 18:08.962
You're right.

18:09.046 --> 18:11.006
You are absolutely right,
but what am I supposed to do?

18:11.089 --> 18:12.800
If I throw this out,
I will have to do

18:12.883 --> 18:14.009
a page one rewrite by tomorrow.

18:14.092 --> 18:15.803
I can't do that,
I will be a basket case.

18:15.886 --> 18:17.304
I don't even know
what I would write about.

18:17.387 --> 18:18.347
I mean, how do I know that

18:18.430 --> 18:21.099
that speech would be any better
than this speech?

18:21.183 --> 18:22.017
You know what?

18:22.100 --> 18:24.228
I may as well tell them
I have laryngitis

18:24.311 --> 18:26.313
because at this point,
Brandon, it would not be so far

18:26.396 --> 18:28.690
from the truth, my throat
is killing me, I don't even...

18:28.774 --> 18:30.526
Andrea, get a grip
on yourself, would ya?

18:30.609 --> 18:32.319
Look at yourself, relax.

18:32.402 --> 18:33.612
You're having a panic attack.

18:33.695 --> 18:37.241
{\an1}The speech
is not that bad.

18:37.324 --> 18:40.160
It just needs
a little fine-tuning.

18:40.244 --> 18:42.162
In fact, I'll help you with it

18:42.246 --> 18:44.039
for as long as it takes, okay?

18:47.292 --> 18:50.671
{\an3}Brandon...
how am I going to get

18:50.754 --> 18:52.172
through college without you?

18:52.256 --> 18:55.300
I'm sure you'll manage.

18:56.760 --> 18:59.680
{\an3}You know, the day you
walked into that newsroom,

18:59.763 --> 19:02.724
{\an3}I knew...<i> knew</i> that
you were special.

19:02.808 --> 19:05.227
{\an1}You thought I was tripe
the first time you met me.

19:05.310 --> 19:06.395
Yeah.

19:06.478 --> 19:08.397
But that all changed
after you followed me home

19:08.480 --> 19:11.233
to my parents'
house in Van Nuys.

19:11.316 --> 19:14.403
That is the day that I knew
that I could trust you.

19:14.486 --> 19:16.363
And so began
a beautiful friendship.

19:16.446 --> 19:20.409
Well, it hasn't been
<i>just</i> a friendship, has it?

19:20.492 --> 19:23.245
I guess you could say
our relationship's

19:23.328 --> 19:24.329
had its ups and downs.

19:26.498 --> 19:28.083
{\an1}So what's the big
surprise, huh?

19:28.166 --> 19:31.920
Well, I've, uh...

19:32.004 --> 19:34.631
I've got a going away
present for you.

19:34.715 --> 19:36.341
Well, what is it?

19:38.343 --> 19:42.139
Uh, well, um...

19:42.222 --> 19:44.433
(giggles):
Ta-da...

19:44.516 --> 19:48.228
What?

19:48.312 --> 19:50.105
The carousel, the horse, what?

19:50.188 --> 19:52.316
No, I'm....

19:52.399 --> 19:55.444
I'm giving you
the person on my horse.

19:55.527 --> 19:59.072
Uh, if you'll take her.

19:59.156 --> 20:02.284
What?

20:04.328 --> 20:09.207
Look, Brandon, we may never
see each other again and I...

20:09.291 --> 20:11.418
I want good-bye to be
a moment we both remember.

20:20.093 --> 20:21.136
{\an3}Oh, my God!

20:21.219 --> 20:23.472
{\an3}I know exactly why this
speech isn't working.

20:23.555 --> 20:24.765
Why?

20:24.848 --> 20:26.767
Because it's not
coming from the heart.

20:26.850 --> 20:28.143
It is exactly like you said.

20:28.226 --> 20:31.104
I am trying to live up
to this image of being a Yalie,

20:31.188 --> 20:32.356
when I know deep inside
I should probably

20:32.439 --> 20:35.150
just stay in town and go
to California University.

20:35.233 --> 20:37.611
Andrea, you've got
to go to Yale.

20:37.694 --> 20:39.363
You can't give that up
because of me, I'm not worth it.

20:39.446 --> 20:42.324
It's true that we challenge

20:42.407 --> 20:44.785
and support each other and all
that, it's very true.

20:44.868 --> 20:46.787
{\an3}But we just don't have
the kind of relationship

20:46.870 --> 20:47.537
that you should give up
your life's dream for.

20:47.621 --> 20:49.498
Just hold it, okay, Brandon.

20:49.581 --> 20:53.043
You are starting
to sound like me.

20:55.128 --> 20:57.381
{\an1}Yes.?

20:57.464 --> 20:59.049
If I don't go
to school back East,

20:59.132 --> 21:02.344
it's because I don't want to be
in hock for the rest of my life.

21:02.427 --> 21:04.137
I mean, do you know how
expensive Yale is?

21:04.221 --> 21:08.016
I think I have
a pretty good idea.

21:10.310 --> 21:12.854
Sorry I jumped to conclusions.

21:12.938 --> 21:16.191
It's okay.

21:20.487 --> 21:23.198
(knocking)

21:24.491 --> 21:25.993
{\an1}Hi, Smush.

21:26.451 --> 21:29.621
{\an1}Kel, if you tell anybody
that I let you call me that

21:29.705 --> 21:30.539
(TV playing)u.

21:30.622 --> 21:31.540
Well, my lips are sealed.

21:31.623 --> 21:34.501
{\an1}That's the way
I like them.

21:34.584 --> 21:35.877
What are you watching?

21:35.961 --> 21:37.546
Oh, I'm not really watching.

21:37.629 --> 21:40.590
I was just sort of reading
about California University.

21:40.674 --> 21:43.385
Yeah.eally?

21:43.468 --> 21:44.845
I think we'd have
a good time here.

21:44.928 --> 21:46.096
You think so, huh?

21:46.179 --> 21:48.015
{\an3}Well, my dad was real
high on the idea

21:48.098 --> 21:49.599
{\an3}of me going
to college, so...

21:49.683 --> 21:52.394
{\an3}I don't know, I figure
I'll check it out

21:52.477 --> 21:53.729
for a little while.

21:53.812 --> 21:56.023
{\an1}I suppose, but the thought
of going back to school

21:56.106 --> 21:57.607
{\an1}for four more years
is just overwhelming.

21:57.691 --> 22:02.112
{\an3}Well, at least we'll be
overwhelmed together.

22:02.195 --> 22:04.906
{\an1}You've used that
line on me before.

22:04.990 --> 22:06.867
Yes, you have.

22:06.950 --> 22:08.118
When?

22:08.201 --> 22:09.703
The night in the pool.

22:12.497 --> 22:13.790
{\an3}KELLY:
This was a good idea.

22:13.874 --> 22:15.667
I'm full of good ideas.

22:18.253 --> 22:20.255
(Kelly laughs)

22:32.184 --> 22:33.560
{\an1}Don't do that
if you don't mean it.

22:33.643 --> 22:35.562
I mean it.

22:35.645 --> 22:38.482
Well, you're in trouble now.

22:48.658 --> 22:50.577
{\an1}Dylan, what if Brenda
had come tonight?

22:50.660 --> 22:51.578
{\an3}(laughs)

22:51.661 --> 22:53.455
{\an3}She didn't.

22:53.538 --> 22:54.581
So is that how you
made up your mind?

22:54.664 --> 22:55.582
'Cause she's not here?

22:55.665 --> 22:58.919
Maybe.

23:00.545 --> 23:04.508
Mel and my mom are breaking up
because he was fooling around.

23:04.591 --> 23:07.469
I just can't feel that great
about being the other woman.

23:07.552 --> 23:10.472
{\an3}Look, it was you two who
gave me that dumb ultimatum.

23:10.555 --> 23:11.890
You said choose.

23:11.973 --> 23:14.643
I chose and I chose you.

23:14.726 --> 23:17.145
I want you.

23:17.229 --> 23:18.855
I've always wanted you.

23:19.856 --> 23:22.651
(doorbell ringing)

23:22.734 --> 23:25.153
{\an1}Why does this always
happen to us?

23:25.237 --> 23:27.322
{\an3}(sighing):
Don't move.

23:29.699 --> 23:31.618
Who is it?

23:31.701 --> 23:33.620
Dylan, it's me.

23:33.703 --> 23:34.579
It's my mother.

23:34.663 --> 23:36.957
(huffs)

23:37.040 --> 23:39.376
Unbelievable.

23:41.294 --> 23:42.629
Hi!

23:42.712 --> 23:44.923
(sighs)

23:45.006 --> 23:45.924
What a pleasant surprise.

23:46.007 --> 23:49.177
{\an3}Did you really think I'd
miss your graduation?

23:49.261 --> 23:50.637
You missed practically
everything else in my life.

23:50.720 --> 23:54.349
Oh, you're in a snarly mood.

23:54.432 --> 23:56.184
{\an1}Aren't you the least bit
tickled to see me?

23:56.268 --> 23:57.227
I'm stunned actually.

23:57.310 --> 23:58.812
{\an3}Can't you pick up the
phone like a normal person

23:58.895 --> 24:00.355
{\an3}and call and let me
know that you're coming?

24:00.438 --> 24:01.690
Because I was afraid
you'd tell me to stay home

24:01.773 --> 24:05.569
and I was hoping we could
spend a few days together.

24:05.652 --> 24:07.571
Besides, half the fun
is catching you

24:07.654 --> 24:09.156
with a girl in the bedroom.

24:09.239 --> 24:10.615
{\an1}Did I, did I catch you
with a girl in the bedroom?

24:10.699 --> 24:13.076
No, no, you didn't,
we were on the couch.

24:13.160 --> 24:14.077
Kelly!

24:14.161 --> 24:15.704
You're still with Kelly?

24:15.787 --> 24:17.080
You know, you barge in here,

24:17.164 --> 24:18.915
{\an3}you expect me to welcome
you with open arms

24:18.999 --> 24:19.875
{\an3}when the fact
of the matter is

24:19.958 --> 24:21.710
{\an3}when I needed you,
you were unreachable.

24:21.793 --> 24:22.711
I was on a trek in the Andes.

24:22.794 --> 24:25.213
{\an3}Oh, yeah, I was just
at my father's funeral.

24:25.297 --> 24:27.757
{\an3}And I called you
as soon as I Right.

24:27.841 --> 24:29.718
What'd you expect? It was
bad timing, you and I, huh?

24:29.801 --> 24:30.594
(clears throat)

24:30.677 --> 24:33.013
Hi, Kelly.

24:33.096 --> 24:35.390
I would love to stop and chat,
but apparently this visit

24:35.473 --> 24:36.975
is going to be shorter
than I thought.

24:37.058 --> 24:37.934
What's it going to be?

24:38.018 --> 24:39.394
The Hilton or the Bel Age?

24:39.477 --> 24:40.562
That wilIt's on me.cessary.

24:40.645 --> 24:44.065
So I see I've outlived
my usefulness

24:44.149 --> 24:45.775
now you're
a full-fledged millionaire.

24:45.859 --> 24:46.735
{\an3}DYLAN:
Yeah, reservations, please.

24:46.818 --> 24:48.737
Did he rush right out
and get a Gold Card?

24:48.820 --> 24:50.530
Hi, this is
Dylan McKay.

24:50.614 --> 24:51.531
{\an3}I need your
best suite

24:51.615 --> 24:52.199
for Iris McKay.

24:52.282 --> 24:55.368
Make sure it's non-smoking.

24:55.452 --> 24:57.370
I'm sorry.

24:57.454 --> 24:58.914
No, don't apologize, dear.

24:58.997 --> 24:59.748
Just be careful.

24:59.831 --> 25:01.583
Money changes people.

25:01.666 --> 25:05.086
{\an3}Yeah, my account
number: 6-4-2-8...

25:05.170 --> 25:05.795
0-0-6-1...

25:05.879 --> 25:08.757
3-7-7-4-4-4.

25:17.349 --> 25:18.642
(piano playing)

25:18.725 --> 25:21.436
♪ Overture, curtain lights ♪

25:21.519 --> 25:22.312
♪ Overture, curtain lights... ♪

25:22.395 --> 25:23.980
{\an1}Andrea, Andrea,
you knock it off already?

25:24.064 --> 25:24.648
{\an1}Your speech is
already a hundred times

25:24.731 --> 25:25.774
better than it was.

25:25.857 --> 25:28.693
{\an3}Well, since I started off
in the negative column,

25:28.777 --> 25:29.778
{\an3}that just puts me back
to zero, doesn't it?

25:29.861 --> 25:30.862
I give up, I give up.

25:30.946 --> 25:32.864
(Steve laughs)

25:32.948 --> 25:33.782
{\an1}Bran, some of these
senior wills are hysterical.

25:33.865 --> 25:34.783
Tell Andrea, would you?

25:34.866 --> 25:37.285
{\an3}Try to lighten her
up a little bit.

25:37.369 --> 25:38.411
It's my specialty.

25:38.495 --> 25:40.163
Get on it, brother.

25:40.247 --> 25:43.166
Okay, Zuckerman, time to get
in the Senior Breakfast mode.

25:43.250 --> 25:44.626
{\an3}Can I have the
pad back, please?

25:44.709 --> 25:46.461
{\an1}Not until you acknowledge
what I left you

25:46.544 --> 25:47.671
in the Senior Wills.

25:48.880 --> 25:50.632
♪ Overture, curtain lights... ♪

25:50.715 --> 25:53.426
Great, an egg.

25:53.510 --> 25:55.178
{\an3}Are you implying that
that's what I'm gonna lay

25:55.262 --> 25:55.845
when I give my speech?

25:55.929 --> 25:56.846
{\an1}Andrea,
don't you remember

25:56.930 --> 25:58.807
{\an1}when we went
to exchange the egg?

25:58.890 --> 26:01.142
We drove around all night

26:01.226 --> 26:01.810
looking for that
underground club?

26:01.893 --> 26:03.895
Right.

26:03.979 --> 26:05.647
DonThe egg exchange!hat?

26:05.730 --> 26:07.107
Come on, that lady
in, in that store?

26:10.527 --> 26:12.821
Hi, I'd like to exchange an egg.

26:12.904 --> 26:15.490
You want to exchange an egg?

26:15.573 --> 26:17.659
{\an3}Do you have
a receipt?

26:17.742 --> 26:19.452
No.

26:19.536 --> 26:20.495
Do I need a receipt?

26:20.578 --> 26:22.455
{\an1}I mean, is that
part of the thing?

26:22.539 --> 26:23.999
It's customary to have a receipt

26:24.082 --> 26:24.833
when you want
to exchange something.

26:24.916 --> 26:26.835
{\an1}I think we're
in the wrong place.

26:26.918 --> 26:29.629
{\an3}No, no, this is all
part of the deal.

26:29.713 --> 26:31.673
Watch.

26:31.756 --> 26:35.468
{\an3}I want to...
<i>exchange</i> an eg.

26:35.552 --> 26:36.469
Look, Steve,

26:36.553 --> 26:37.095
{\an3}let's go.

26:37.178 --> 26:38.847
What's wrong with the egg?

26:38.930 --> 26:40.473
Nothing.

26:40.557 --> 26:41.349
But you want another?

26:41.433 --> 26:43.351
{\an6}(chuckling):
No, I don't want
another egg.

26:43.435 --> 26:44.311
I want information.

26:44.394 --> 26:46.813
Look, I don't know
what you kids are on,

26:46.896 --> 26:49.983
{\an3}but I'm calling
the police.

26:50.066 --> 26:52.235
{\an3}You know, I think we're
in the wrong place.

26:52.319 --> 26:54.362
(Andrea laughing)

26:57.324 --> 26:58.033
{\an1}BRANDON:
Hey, hey, hey, hey.

26:58.116 --> 27:00.410
Hey, what's so funny?

27:00.493 --> 27:02.620
{\an1}You had
to be there.

27:09.794 --> 27:10.670
Brenda, forget it.

27:10.754 --> 27:12.339
{\an1}You cannot leave me
the double date from Hell

27:12.422 --> 27:13.006
{\an1}and not tell me
what their names were.

27:13.089 --> 27:15.216
Okay, I'll give you a hint.

27:15.300 --> 27:16.968
Wayne.

27:17.052 --> 27:17.844
And Adam. Ugh!

27:17.927 --> 27:19.929
Don't you remember?

27:20.013 --> 27:22.849
My mom set these guys up on
a blind date with the two geeks.

27:22.932 --> 27:26.061
{\an3}Right, the <i> men,</i>
bro, from Princeton.

27:32.692 --> 27:34.778
This is Wayne
and this is Adam.

27:34.861 --> 27:39.282
{\an3}This is Brenda
and Kelly.

27:39.366 --> 27:41.117
Oh, wow.

27:41.201 --> 27:42.535
Thank you, God.

27:42.619 --> 27:43.536
{\an1}You guys
don't really

27:43.620 --> 27:45.246
{\an3}go to Princeton,
do you?

27:45.330 --> 27:47.040
Yeah, yeah, we do.

27:47.123 --> 27:48.917
{\an1}We go to the Princeton
School in Encino.

27:49.000 --> 27:50.752
{\an3}Yeah, making
boys into men.

27:50.835 --> 27:54.089
Brenda.

27:54.172 --> 27:57.717
{\an3}Uh, see, we thought that
you were college guys.

27:58.843 --> 28:01.763
Oh... okay.

28:01.846 --> 28:03.932
{\an1}Well... we don't have to go
out if you don't want to.

28:04.015 --> 28:08.686
{\an6}CINDY:
No, no, of course
you're going out.

28:10.313 --> 28:13.066
{\an1}We are going
to have so much fun.

28:13.149 --> 28:14.317
I can just feel it.

28:14.401 --> 28:15.735
(group laughing)

28:17.529 --> 28:18.822
{\an4}(sighing):
They took us
to a video arcade.

28:18.905 --> 28:20.782
{\an3}That had to be the funniest
night I had all year.

28:20.865 --> 28:21.783
Are you sure
about that?

28:21.866 --> 28:24.119
{\an1}Did you see
what <i> I</i> left you?

28:24.202 --> 28:25.120
What?

28:25.203 --> 28:26.955
<i>Cervelle de vea?</i>

28:27.038 --> 28:28.623
(lOh.hs)

28:28.706 --> 28:29.791
What's that mean?

28:29.874 --> 28:31.000
<i>Je ne sais pas.</i>

28:31.084 --> 28:32.794
{\an3}Okay, you guys have
got to remember

28:32.877 --> 28:34.629
{\an3}that was our first
night in Paris, right?

28:34.712 --> 28:36.256
Awful plane ride.

28:36.339 --> 28:39.134
{\an5}(laughing):
All we wanted was a really,
really, really good meal.

28:39.217 --> 28:40.260
(speaks French)

28:40.343 --> 28:41.261
Oh, here.

28:41.344 --> 28:43.263
Whoops.

28:47.684 --> 28:49.686
Bren, this is all in French.

28:51.563 --> 28:55.859
Oh, um, oh, God.

28:55.942 --> 28:57.068
{\an3}(enunciating):
I don't want fish.

28:59.904 --> 29:01.406
(laughs nervously)

29:01.489 --> 29:03.783
One, one sec.

29:10.123 --> 29:12.625
This, please.

29:12.709 --> 29:13.710
<i>S'il vous plaî.</i>

29:13.793 --> 29:15.128
{\an1}<i>Cervelle de veau,</i>
<i>très bien.</i>

29:15.211 --> 29:16.129
What's that?

29:16.212 --> 29:16.838
<i>Veau</i> is veal.

29:16.921 --> 29:18.756
Ooh, that sounds good.

29:18.840 --> 29:19.174
Garcon, make that two.

29:19.257 --> 29:21.759
<i>Très bien.</i>

29:22.844 --> 29:25.305
{\an1}You see, that wasn't
so hard, was it?

29:25.388 --> 29:26.306
Bon appétit.

29:26.389 --> 29:27.849
Bon appétit.

29:27.932 --> 29:30.810
<i>Cervelle de veau.</i>

29:33.938 --> 29:35.356
(scoffs)

29:35.440 --> 29:37.859
Wait a second.

29:37.942 --> 29:39.527
I ordered veal.

29:39.611 --> 29:41.863
<i>Me oui, cervelle de veau.</i>

29:41.946 --> 29:43.531
Bon appétit.

29:43.615 --> 29:47.494
Okay, it looks weird,
but I'm sure it's edible.

29:47.577 --> 29:48.703
You're right.

29:48.786 --> 29:50.121
About now I could eat
just about anything.

30:01.257 --> 30:04.761
It's very, uh... French.

30:04.844 --> 30:08.014
It's, uh, it's kind of mushy.

30:17.315 --> 30:19.192
It's brains.

30:19.275 --> 30:22.278
(group laughing)

30:26.783 --> 30:29.536
{\an3}How could
you do that?

30:29.619 --> 30:30.787
Donna, Donna, we're on soon.

30:30.870 --> 30:32.247
We've still got
to get into costume.

30:32.330 --> 30:33.248
Okay, let's go.

30:33.331 --> 30:34.415
Break a leg.

30:34.499 --> 30:36.751
{\an6}BRANDON:
How could you
order veal anyway?

30:36.834 --> 30:38.086
{\an3}STEVE:
I like veal, I like veal.

30:38.169 --> 30:40.088
(all talking)

30:40.171 --> 30:41.714
{\an3}Au revoir,
Mademoiselle Donna.

30:41.798 --> 30:42.715
Have fun.

30:42.799 --> 30:44.425
{\an3}<i>Me ou.</i>

30:44.509 --> 30:47.428
{\an3}That's a pretty funny
bit with the cow brains.

30:47.512 --> 30:49.764
{\an3}(chuckles)

30:49.847 --> 30:52.058
What's the matter?

30:52.141 --> 30:53.434
{\an1}I really loved being
in Paris,

30:53.518 --> 30:55.103
{\an1}but I can't help wondering
what would be

30:55.186 --> 30:58.273
if I hadn't gone.

31:04.737 --> 31:07.198
Does anybody else know you've
been accepted to Minnesota?

31:13.538 --> 31:14.914
Okay.

31:14.998 --> 31:15.873
Get this.

31:15.957 --> 31:17.792
{\an1}Some people would rather live
in Beverly Hills

31:17.875 --> 31:19.127
{\an1}than here
in Aurora, Illinois.

31:19.210 --> 31:20.378
{\an3}No way.

31:20.461 --> 31:22.130
And they actually say
that it's kind of cool

31:22.213 --> 31:23.131
{\an1}to go
to West Beverly High.

31:23.214 --> 31:25.508
{\an3}No Way.

31:25.592 --> 31:27.427
{\an3}No Way!

31:27.510 --> 31:29.637
{\an1}And these same people
also say...

31:29.721 --> 31:33.516
{\an5}BOTH:
Live from West Beverly High,
it's the Senior Breakfast!

31:33.600 --> 31:35.310
(crowd cheering)

31:41.524 --> 31:44.527
{\an6}STEVE:
It's the Senior
Breakfast with...

31:44.611 --> 31:47.655
David Silver, Donna Martin,

31:47.739 --> 31:50.491
Mrs. T. and the class of '93,

31:50.575 --> 31:51.826
special musical guest

31:51.909 --> 31:53.661
the Wildcat Singers.

31:53.745 --> 31:55.163
{\an3}And here he
is now...

31:55.246 --> 31:59.626
David Silver!

32:00.627 --> 32:02.795
Thank you, thank you.

32:02.879 --> 32:03.796
Thank you, Steve.

32:03.880 --> 32:05.590
Could you please come up here
for a minute?

32:05.673 --> 32:08.509
{\an1}Come on.

32:08.593 --> 32:10.553
{\an1}Now, somebody found
something

32:10.637 --> 32:12.138
and they, they thought
it might belong to you.

32:12.221 --> 32:14.849
Oh, yep, it's a legacy key.

32:14.932 --> 32:16.684
{\an1}They say it unlocks
every door

32:16.768 --> 32:18.519
{\an1}to every boys' bathroom
in the entire school.

32:18.603 --> 32:19.437
(crowd cheering)

32:21.272 --> 32:24.567
{\an3}Aren't you late for
detention, Steve?

32:25.777 --> 32:27.695
Let's hear it for Steve.

32:27.779 --> 32:29.906
(crowd cheering)

32:29.989 --> 32:32.992
And let's hear it for my partner
in crime Donna Martin.

32:34.619 --> 32:36.037
Whoo, whoo, whoo!

32:36.120 --> 32:37.580
Whoo!

32:38.164 --> 32:41.584
{\an1}Okay, now, I know most
of you have seen

32:41.668 --> 32:43.086
David's video yearbook,

32:43.169 --> 32:45.588
{\an1}but we thought you'd like
to see some of the outtakes

32:45.672 --> 32:47.215
{\an1}that didn't make it
on the reel,

32:47.298 --> 32:48.383
{\an1}starting
with the camping trip

32:48.466 --> 32:50.385
{\an1}that some of us
will never forget.

32:50.468 --> 32:52.220
He's not going
to show that.

32:52.303 --> 32:56.057
{\an5}DAVID:
It's a brand new morning
here at Hukamuk Lodge

32:56.140 --> 32:57.725
and as you can see,

32:57.809 --> 32:59.686
some campers tend
to be less bright-eyed

32:59.769 --> 33:02.397
and bushy-tailed than others.

33:02.480 --> 33:05.024
We've heard tell of some wild
boar living in these parts.

33:05.108 --> 33:07.985
STEVE:
Give me a break, okay?

33:08.069 --> 33:10.279
Oh, isn't it a little early
for this, David?

33:11.823 --> 33:12.281
David, get out!

33:12.365 --> 33:14.242
(Steve blowing nose)

33:14.325 --> 33:17.620
BRENDA (on video):
Steve, what are you doing?

33:17.704 --> 33:19.414
STEVE:
Leave me alone.

33:19.497 --> 33:21.582
{\an5}KELLY:
He's clearing his sinuses
or so he claims.

33:21.666 --> 33:22.875
STEVE:
It's true.

33:22.959 --> 33:24.752
BRENDA:
I am starving...

33:26.713 --> 33:28.631
{\an3}Man, this
is beautiful.

33:31.843 --> 33:33.261
{\an3}Brandon!

33:33.344 --> 33:34.220
Oh!

33:34.303 --> 33:36.222
{\an3}Brandon!

33:37.390 --> 33:39.600
Where are you at, man?

33:39.684 --> 33:41.811
(sBrandon!)

33:41.894 --> 33:44.522
Dylan, get back, man,
the ledge is going to go.

33:44.605 --> 33:46.232
All right, man, grab my hand.

33:46.315 --> 33:48.985
I-I can't, man, I can't let go.

33:49.068 --> 33:50.486
You gotta try.

33:51.320 --> 33:53.781
Come on.

33:54.741 --> 33:56.242
(grunts)

33:56.325 --> 33:57.118
Don't look down.

33:57.201 --> 33:59.120
Look up here.

33:59.203 --> 34:00.371
Look right here.

34:10.380 --> 34:12.091
All right, come on.

34:12.175 --> 34:13.259
(both grunting)

34:21.893 --> 34:22.768
(applause)

34:22.851 --> 34:24.812
{\an3}And for being so graceful
on the gridiron,

34:24.896 --> 34:27.190
your trophies.

34:27.273 --> 34:29.942
{\an3}Let's give it up for
the varsity backfield.

34:30.025 --> 34:31.944
{\an1}You're dead,
Silver.

34:32.027 --> 34:34.655
Thank you, Tony.

34:34.739 --> 34:38.159
And now, Brenda Walsh
and Kelly Taylor, come on down.

34:38.242 --> 34:40.661
Hey, now.

34:40.745 --> 34:42.955
Here goes nothing.

34:52.590 --> 34:54.509
Now, you guys don't know this,

34:54.592 --> 34:57.136
but Brenda and Kelly are the
only students at West Beverly

34:57.220 --> 34:59.889
to ever win a prize
on a radio call-in show

34:59.972 --> 35:01.974
and I don't think either
of them will ever forget

35:02.058 --> 35:02.809
{\an1}the prize
that they won.

35:02.892 --> 35:06.854
{\an3}Okay, everybody,
watch the monitors.

35:07.814 --> 35:08.981
I don't know, Kel.

35:09.065 --> 35:11.526
This might have to be
a solo mission on your part.

35:11.609 --> 35:12.360
{\an5}KELLY:
Brenda, I couldn't do that
to you.

35:12.443 --> 35:14.237
You're my best friend.

35:15.446 --> 35:16.989
{\an3}I have to help you
face your fears.

35:17.073 --> 35:17.990
No, Kelly!

35:18.074 --> 35:22.078
(both screaming)

35:29.126 --> 35:31.712
This is so amazing!

35:31.796 --> 35:32.755
Brenda, get me down!

35:32.839 --> 35:34.257
(both screaming)

35:37.260 --> 35:39.387
(cheering and applause)

35:44.809 --> 35:47.270
{\an3}Here's a little memento
of that experience

35:47.353 --> 35:48.271
for both of you.

35:48.354 --> 35:50.857
{\an3}Thanks.

35:50.940 --> 35:52.191
But don't go yet

35:52.275 --> 35:54.360
{\an3}because I want you guys and
Donna to turn the clocks back

35:54.443 --> 35:56.696
and say hello

35:56.779 --> 35:58.489
to Hello Day.

